[Student "S"]
{Two choices come to mind - 2NT or 2\H.

Of the two, 2\H is better because it prevents a possible 4-4 \H fit from being lost. Partner rebids his \Ss.

Two opening hands equal one game. Since partner has 6 \S that game might as well be 4\S. 

South would play 4\S.

Click 

North plays 4\S. East leads the \CJ. They play two more high \Cs.

<b>North plays 4\S. East leads the \CJ. They play two more high \Cs.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 2 : \D 0 : \C 2 : Total = 4

You ruff the third \C, then play \SQ and \SJ. Come to your hand with the \DA and pull the last trump. Now decide what to do with the \Hs.

If East has both \HK and \HQ then a simple finesse of the \HJ will bring in the contract. This is only a 25% chance.

If the high \H honors are split, but East holds the \H10 then a finesse of the \H9 will force West to win with his high honor. You can return to your hand and then finesse East out of his other \H honor. This play has about a 50% chance of working so it is the one you should make.

This is called a Deep Finesse. 

The only time it is a mistake is when East holds the \H K Q and West holds the \H10. Even in that case though some Wests will "split their honors" and give it away.}
[Play "W"]CJ

